did.abstract: Records of the International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers, Local 46

bioghist.p: The International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers was founded in St. Louis, Missouri in 1890, when a group of electrical workers got together and chartered the National Brotherhood of Electrical Workers Local 5221 under the leadership of its first president, Henry Miller. Local 217 of Seattle, Washington was established in 1901 and ordered defunct in 1908. For six years, dissenting forces within the union caused a split, with each side electing its own officers. The AFL ultimately deemed the McNulty-Collins faction as the legitimate brotherhood. In 1914, the IBEW Local 46 was formed in Seattle with a membership of 250 men of various occupations: inside wiremen, marine wiremen, radio workers and telephone operators that worked in shipyards, industrial areas, uptown Seattle and its vicinity. Over the years the departments of the IBEW grew to include Sound and Communication, Residential, Marine, HVAC, Electronics, Motor Shop, Neon Sign and Maintenance. Current Local 46 jurisdiction includes King, Kitsap, Jefferson and Clallam Counties. Today, Local 46 is composed of over 4,500 members in a variety of craft units as well as over 1200 associate members.

arrangement.p: Organized into 2 accessions.

Accession No. 5739-002, International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers, Local 46 records, 1902-2014

scopecontent.p: This collection documents the various activities of several branches of International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers Local 46 located in the Seattle, Washington and its surrounding areas. The bulk of the collection contains papers that originated in the Seattle branch 46 of the IBEW, as well as documents that were collected at the time of its creation as well as through subsequent mergers. The documents are from the various committees and units of Local 46, as well as some geographical offshoots of Local 46. The collection details the activities of the Union and its members, as well as the relations between the Union and employers.

arrangement.p: The collection is arranged into 7 series.

Membership Records & Dues (Series I), Meeting Minutes & Registers (Series II) and Publications and Reports (Series VII) are arranged according to originating body. Contract Negotiations (Series III), Office Files (Series IV), Financial Records (Series V) and Education/Training (Series VI) are arranged by function. Within these subseries, files are arranged chronologically by date of the oldest document in the file. Contract Negotiations (Series III) is arranged alphabetically within the subseries.

scopecontent.p: The largest part of the collection is the Meeting Minutes & Registers (Series II), which document the issues most pertinent to the Union and its members. Another large portion of the collection is Contract Negotiations (Series III), which showcases the evolvement of contracts, and workers rights as a whole, over time. Of particular note are the files involving the IBEW Local 46’s correspondence and negotiations with KIRO Incorporated and Fisher Broadcasting Incorporated, which offer insight into discord between employers, employees and the union. The day-to-day workings of the IBEW can be assessed from Membership Records & Dues (Series I), Office Files (Series IV), Financial Records (Series V) and Education/Training (Series VI). In addition, Publications & Reports (Series VII) offers some more general union information as found in serial publications.

scopecontent.p: Series I includes detailed Membership Records & Dues for the general membership of Local 46 from 1930-1945, as well as a handful of departmental Membership Records & Dues. The series also includes Application Fees and Permit Hands related to the membership records of the late 1930s to early 1940s.

arrangement.p: The series is subdivided by originating body: Subseries A: General Membership Records & Dues; Subseries B: Business Agent Membership Records; Subseries C: A Member Records; Subseries D: Seattle Building Fund Membership Records & Dues; Subseries E: Application Fees; Subseries F: Permit Hands. Subseries A: General Membership Records & Dues is further arranged chronologically.

scopecontent.p: Series II includes extensive minutes for Local 46 and it’s numerous departments. The General Meeting Minutes and Executive Board Meeting Minutes are complete and span from the 1920s-1970s. The bulk of the other departmental minutes are from the 1950s-1980s.

arrangement.p: The series is subdivided by the originating departmental body within Local 46: Subseries A: General Board Meeting Minutes Local 217; Subseries B: General Board Meeting Minutes Local 46; Subseries C: Executive Board Meeting Minutes Local 46; Subseries D: Joint Executive Board Minutes Local 46 and Local 77; Subseries E: Retired Members Club of IBEW Meeting Minutes; Subseries F: Wireman's Unit Meeting Minutes; Subseries G: Marine Unit Meeting Minutes; Subseries H: Building Fund Managers Meeting Minutes; Subseries I: E.F.E. Unit Meeting Minutes; Subseries J: Manufacturing Unit Meeting Minutes; Subseries K: Motor Shop Unit Meeting Minutes; Subseries L: N.Y.E. Systems Unit Meeting Minutes; Subseries M: Port Angeles Unit Meeting Minutes; Subseries N: Bremerton Unit Meeting Register & Minutes; Subseries O: Broadcast Unit Meeting Register & Minutes; Subseries P: Cranemen Local 241 Meeting Minutes; Subseries Q: Neon/Electrical Sign Unit Meeting Register & Minutes; Subseries R: Oil Burner Unit Meeting Register & Minutes; Subseries S: Electronics Unit Meeting Register & Minutes; Subseries T: Electrical Workers Benefit Association Meeting Minutes. Each subseries is further arranged chronologically

scopecontent.p: Series III includes contracts and letters of assent between Local 46 and its numerous contracted companies, as well as correspondence, benefit bonds and voting records that relate to contract negotiations. In addition there are grievances filed by union members and employers, National Labor Relations Board cases and settlements made with Local 46 that exemplify the ongoing disputes that occurred when employers and/or union members failed to live up to the contract expectations.

arrangement.p: The series is divided into two subseries based on the distinctly different parts of the office in which each set of files was located: Subseries A: Contract Negotiations Part 1; Subseries B: Contract Negotiations Part 2. It is unclear why the office chose to divide them this way. Within each subseries files are arranged alphabetically. Many of the files in Subseries B: Contract Negotiations Part 2 have a departmental label (Inside Wire; Residential; Stockmen; Sound & Communication, etc.) in parentheses after the company name.

Series II: Dispatch Books and Registers

arrangement.p: Meeting Minutes and Registers (Series I), Dispatch Books and Registers (Series II), Conferences and Conventions (Series VI), and Publications and Reports (Series VII) are arranged into subseries according to originating body. Contract Negotiations (Series III), Office Files (Series IV), and Photographs and Historical Materials (Series VIII) are arranged into subseries by function. Financial Records (Series V), is not divided into subseries. Contract Negotiations (Series III), is arranged alphabetically within each subseries. All other subseries, and Financial Records (Series V), are arranged chronologically according to the oldest document in each file.

scopecontent.p: A large part of the collection is the Meeting Minutes & Registers (Series I), which document the issues most pertinent to the Union and its members. Another large portion of the collection is Publications and Reports (Series VII), which contains publications collected by officers of Local 46 as well as a long history of newsletters, papers and reports published by the union. Another large portion of the collection is Contract Negotiations (Series III), which showcases the evolvement of contracts, and workers rights as a whole, over time. Of particular note in this collection is the detailed history of the union, put together by Bob Gorman and Local 46’s History Committee, in Photographs and Historical Materials (Series VIII). The day-to-day workings of the IBEW can be assessed from Dispatch Books and Registers (Series II), Office Files (Series IV), and Financial Records (Series V). In addition, Conferences and Conventions (Series VI), offers information, commemorative publications and photographs about various union gatherings such as anniversary celebrations, banquets, official conferences, and large conventions throughout the union’s history.
